	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=10&mid=98395636289514>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=10&mid=98395636289514>RE: The Unappreciated Bow</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=10&mid=98395636289514#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Mar 7th 4:12 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>This is one item that makes an excellent weapon for group tactics, but is almost never used as such. Three bowmen in conjuction with snare and root spells can maul even a numerically superior enemy with hardly a bit of damage in return. The bow gives your casters time to slow the horde down then root one or two at a time while the rest are still taking damage from the arrows as you retreat. Done right you've now got the enemy strung out into managable and immobile groups then you can deal out damage to one creature at a time while taking little (if any) in return with volley fire.<br><br>Its also a good weapon for those of us who tend to respond when those infamous "train to zone"&nbsp;&nbsp;and "help" shouts are heard. A single well placed shot (especially a critical with a high-damage arrow) can taunt a monster off someone and make it chase you (thus giving its original target a chance to get away), slow it down from blood lose (giving its target a chance to outrun it), or even make it run away itself.<br><br>Finally, for those of us who are rogues at heart, its much less likely to give away you position before your shot hits than a spells flashy (and highly visible, especially at night) lights, giving you the chance to dissappear again or follow up with a rush into melee before the target can spot you. Imagine a targets suprise on PvP when he hears that he's been hit for 20 points of non-melee damage but can't identify where the attack came from. With good cover (large trees and folds in the ground come to mind) and the hide ability you can fire, duck or hide out of sight, move to a new position, and repeat. Keep it up and soon your victim will be running around like a dog chasing its tail or cowering in fear - and all because he's looking for spell lights and your not using any.</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
